h3. Reproduction of the behaviour on a vanilla system:
* Setup a new Project (e.g. Test)
* Create a new custom field (any string based type will do it).
* Create a new issue and enter the value "-1" in the new created field. (see *-before.png)
* Save the issue.
* Reopen or view the issue, the value "-1" has disapeared from the custom field. (see *-viewafter.png)

h3. Analysis:
A quick look in the source of Jira (v4.1.2) shows that the OfBizCustomFieldValuePersister class does a check before saving the values to the database. In the method "createValuesInt" which gets called for creating _and_ updating values from custom fields the following check and comment is found:
{code:title=OfBizCustomFieldValuePersister.java}
    private void createValuesInt(CustomField field, Long issueId, PersistenceFieldType persistenceFieldType, Collection values, String parentKey)
    {
// ...
        for (Object value : values)
        {
            if (value == null || "".equals(value) || "-1".equals(value))
            {
                continue;
            } // we don't create null values in the database
// ...
        }
    }
{code}
Where the first two checks prevent any empty or null value (which is comprehensible) the third check prevents any string with the value "-1" from being saved to the database.
Personally i suspect this comes from the handling of "-1" as special value for select lists / radio buttons / etc, but this is clearly unwanted behaviour when it comes to string fields (even when the possibility of a simple value like "-1" is relativly small - it may happen that customers depend on this (for IDs, etcs)).

h3. Proposed fix:
To fix this bug it would be enough to remove the third clause in the above mentioned class and check all custom fields if there is any "usage" of this bug.

h3. Risk:
There is nevertheless the risk that implementations outside of Atlassian may depend on this "undocumented" feature - so fixing this may break other code.

P.S.
We found this bug during our testing, it is filed because we want to help to improve code quality. That said there is currently no loss in functionality since we changed the way we document unused IDs our system.

